{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611611"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16230"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16230"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0,0.02,0.26,0.62]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67619"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8921"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16230"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53071"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"10145"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21231"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22643"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67619"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBreast cancer is the most common malignancy affecting women worldwide. Multiple endogenous and environmental factors influence an individual\u0027s risk of developing this disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a risk factor for developing breast cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Late menarche","Multiple full-term pregnancies","Prolonged breastfeeding","Early menopause","High lifetime oestrogen exposure"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh lifetime oestrogen exposure\u003C/strong\u003E is a well-established risk factor for breast cancer. Oestrogen stimulates breast epithelial cell proliferation, increasing the chance of DNA replication errors and malignant transformation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are actually protective factors:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple full-term pregnancies\u003C/strong\u003E reduce risk through terminal differentiation of breast tissue and reduced lifetime oestrogen exposure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELate menarche\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eearly menopause\u003C/strong\u003E decrease risk by reducing lifetime oestrogen exposure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged breastfeeding\u003C/strong\u003E is protective through similar mechanisms as pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important risk factors include age, family history, genetic mutations (BRCA1/2), obesity, alcohol consumption, and exposure to ionizing radiation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High lifetime oestrogen exposure increases breast cancer risk through prolonged stimulation of breast epithelial cell growth.","Major risk factors for breast cancer include early menarche, late menopause, nulliparity, and obesity.","Pregnancy and breastfeeding reduce breast cancer risk through terminal differentiation of breast tissue and reduced lifetime oestrogen exposure."],"references":["\u0141ukasiewicz S, Czeczelewski M, Forma A, Baj J, Sitarz R, Stanis\u0142awek A. Breast Cancer-Epidemiology, Risk Factors, Classification, Prognostic Markers, and Current Treatment Strategies-An Updated Review. Cancers (Basel). 2021 Aug 25;13(17):4287. doi: 10.3390/cancers13174287. PMID: 34503097; PMCID: PMC8428369.","Obeagu EI, Obeagu GU. Breast cancer: A review of risk factors and diagnosis. Medicine (Baltimore). 2024 Jan 19;103(3):e36905. doi: 10.1097/MD.0000000000036905. PMID: 38241592; PMCID: PMC10798762.","Fakhri N, Chad MA, Lahkim M, Houari A, Dehbi H, Belmouden A, El Kadmiri N. Risk factors for breast cancer in women: an update review. Med Oncol. 2022 Sep 7;39(12):197. doi: 10.1007/s12032-022-01804-x. PMID: 36071255."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53071"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16230"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53071"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T08:14:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T08:14:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8921"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67619"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.eme